[{"content":"<p>A <a href="http://apreport.collegeboard.org/" target="_blank">new report</a> shows the number of high school students taking Advanced Placement exams has nearly doubled in the last decade. At $89 a pop — though a low-income subsidy is available — the millions of tests add up to a lot of revenue for the College Board, the non-profit that runs the AP program.</p>","type":"text/html"},{"type":"text/html","content":"<p>Those revenues are rising as more and more students and parents come to see AP classes as vital to getting into college in an increasingly competitive admissions environment.</p>"},{"content":"<p><script src="//ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/static/modules/gviz/1.0/chart.js" type="text/javascript">
